Energy metabolism in myocardium 

Tuesday, May 2, 2017 

8:02 AM 

Provide an overview of ATP production from glucose 

1st step: Glycolysis 

This occurs in the cytoplasm of all cells, generating ATP in both the presence and the absence of oxygen. This process yields 2 pyruvate, 2 ATP, 2 NADH.  

 

2nd step: Krebs cycle 

Pyruvate is oxidised into pyruvic acid. Pyruvic acid is converted to Acetyl-CoA.  

1x Acetyl CoA -> 2CO2 + 3NADH + FADH2 + ATP 

2 turns of the Krebs cycle will occur. 

 

3rd step: Oxygen phosphorylation 

 

Describe the role of oxygen in ATP production in cardiac tissue 

The heart has a continuous, high energy demand for ATP. The heart has very limited anaerobic activity, relying on aerobic metabolism that generates large amounts of ATP by oxidative phosphorylation. Mitochondrial oxidative phosphorylation constitutes the primary energy supply in the myocardial cell. Note that there is a lot of mitochondria in heart cells, filling up to 40% of the cell.  

 

NADH can be oxidised to NAD+, or FADH2 can be oxidised to FAD+.  

The reaction is: NADH -> NAD+ + H+ +  2e- 

Enzymes across the crista of the mitochondria will form the electron transport chain, whereby the electrons are transferred from one to the next eg Coenzyme Q, Cytochrome C, etc. As this process occurs, the enzymes will pump H+ out of the matrix to produce both a concentration and electrochemical gradient. The H+ then flows down its electrochemical gradient (predominantly) through the ATP synthase enzyme (also in crista), whereby conformational changes in the protein synthesise ATP from ADP and phosphate.  

 

Compare the oxygen consumption of myocardium to other tissues 

The myocardium has relatively high oxygen consumption compared to other tissue. The high capillary density of the myocardium allows the extraction of a large fraction of oxygen from the blood. Furthermore, myoglobin in cardiac cells binds O2 and acts as short-term O2 storage, enabling aerobic metabolic generation of ATP.  

 

Myocardial ischemia occurs when there is reduced blood flow/excessive oxygen demand, leading the mitochondrial injury. Myocardial cell damage and death occurs. This causes myoglobin in the blood to be released. 

 

Briefly describe the primary sources of energy for myocardium 

-Fatty acids are the primary substrate for energy production in adult cardiac cells (60-90%) [Beta-oxidation of fatty acids in aerobic metabolism is the primary source of acetyl-CoA for Krebs Cycle] 

-Glucose (less contribution than fatty acids) 

-Ketone bodies, lactate and amino acids 

 

Preference and utilisation rates of each substrate are determined by relative substrate concentration/availability. Furthermore, preference situations do exist: 

 

 

 

Supply of energy to the heart during fasting 

Glycogen stored in liver is a source of glucose for all other organs when fasting between meals. The total reserve is only sufficient for buffering glucose for a few hours. Once glycogen stores are depleted, liver metabolism changes from using glucose (converting them to glycogen) to glucose production (gluconeogenesis), from amino acids, glycerol and lactate (proteolysis, lipolysis).  

 

Fatty acid activation 

Fatty acids are activated into Acyl-CoA in the cytoplasm via Acyl-CoA synthetase: 

Fatty Acid + ATP + CoA -> Acyl-CoA + 2Pi + AMP  

Acyl-CoA is transported into the mitochondria by carnitine, whereby it undergoes beta-oxidation to produce 1 molecule each of NADH, FADH2 and acetyl-CoA per 2 carbons.  

 

Note: a transporter protein, acyl carnitine translocase, is responsible for transferring both the Acyl-CoA into the mitochondria (as Acyl Carnitine), and transferring carnitine out.  A carnitine transport defect causes an enlarged heart and muscle weakness.  

 

Ketone body use in starvation 

Ketone bodies are only produced by the liver from free fatty acids. Ketogenesis occurs in response to prolonged fasting or carbohydrate restriction to meet energy needs.  

 

Lipolysis is stimulated in the adipocytes (adipose cells), and the following occurs: 

 

Areas of usage include heart-muscle cells, renal-cortex cells, and brain cells during starvation.  

 

 

Compare to use of glucose vs fatty acids for energy production 

Fatty-acid use is preferred, as if fully oxidised, a typical fatty acid (palmitate) yields 129 ATP as opposed to 36 ATP from glucose. Triglycerides are furthermore stored in great abundance in the body. This contrasts the limited supply of glucose stores (glycogen), and the notable fluctuation in blood-glucose levels between meals, exercise, etc. Glucose is primarily used as fuel by the brain and red blood cells (RBCs have no mitochondria).  

 

Describe methods of energy storage and discuss limitations of storage for cardiac muscle 

Energy-rich molecules such as glycogen and triglycerides store energy in the form of covalent chemical bonds. The glycogen pool in the heart is small, and there are only small epicardial fat stores. These fat stores can be mobilised to provide fatty acids for energy, but only short-term.  

 

Metabolic release of energy 

-Hydrolysis of liver glycogen stores is the major source of glucose between meals 

-Glycogenolysis provides glucose to skeletal muscle during exercise/fasting 

-Lipolysis (triglyceride breakdown) is a major energy source during starvation 

 

Describe anaerobic vs aerobic glycolysis, and how lactate can be produced and utilised.  

In the absence of O2, there is a buildup of pyruvate and NADH. This pyruvate (formed from glycolysis) will be converted into lactate. This produces a low energy yield of 2ATP as opposed to aerobic glycolysis with 36 ATP.  

 

The ratio of concentration between NAD+ and NADH determines the balance between lactate and pyruvate. 

Tissues with active glycolysis eg Red Blood Cells, skin, brain, skeletal muscle will produce excess lactate from glucose under normal conditions, which tends to spill into the blood. The Lactate Shuttle Hypothesis suggests that lactate produced at these sites can be shuttled to adjacent or remote areas (eg heart, other skeletal muscles, brain, proximal renal tubes), where the lactate can be converted to pyruvate and used as a gluconeogenic precursor 

 

-Lactate is absorbed and metabolised predominantly in the liver, with majority converted back to pyruvate and used to make glucose [and to lesser extent, oxidation to CO2 + water] 

-Blood lactate concentrations reflect the balance between lactate production and clearance. If excessive lactate is produced or cannot be cleared, lactate accumulates and leads to lactate acidosis.
